    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-09-29T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-09-29T02:00:00-05:00" n="49"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d49">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00/473: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Satterthwaite</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-09-29T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 29, 1938—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 29—7:13 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>34. Department’s circular September 27, 4 p.m. The Acting Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs tells me that in the event of a general war Iraq will carry out fully
                    its obligations under Article IV of its Treaty of Alliance with Great
                        Britain<note n="13" xml:id="d49fn13">Signed October 10, 1922; <hi
                            rend="italic">British and Foreign State Papers</hi>, vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">cxix</hi>, p. 389.</note> as well as those under the
                    League Covenant and the Saadabad Pact.<note n="14" xml:id="d49fn14">Signed at
                        Teheran, July 8, 1937, by Afghanistan, Iraq, Iran, and Turkey; League of
                        Nations Treaty Series, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">cxc</hi>, p. 21.</note> The
                    four Foreign Ministers of the latter are now in Geneva and can consult there.
                    Public sympathy seems to have turned toward Great Britain and the Government has
                    not even mentioned the Palestine situation to the British Embassy in assuring it
                    of support.</p>
                <p>I anticipate no disorders and think American citizens here and in the Persian
                    Gulf will be quite safe. There are ample food supplies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Satterthwaite</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
